</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FC94DDA63054FF9D2BB5FE25559CFE5B" pageId="43" pageNumber="194" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B4318E2D3054FF9D2BB5FE255423FE03" blockId="43.[151,1437,151,789]" box="[199,827,402,430]" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">
<emphasis id="86FA523F3054FF9D2BB5FE25567BFE01" bold="true" box="[199,355,402,428]" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="CC99CEBD3054FF9D2A18FE2456D8FE00" box="[362,448,403,429]" name="Mexico" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="764A40CF3054FF9D2ABCFE245520FE00" box="[462,568,403,429]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="764A40CF3054FF9D2931FE24558AFE00" box="[579,658,403,429]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion id="764A40CF3054FF9D29BEFE245436FE03" box="[716,814,403,430]" country="Mexico" name="Morelos" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Morelos</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B4318E2D3054FF9D2BB5FE01559CFE5B" blockId="43.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">
<emphasis id="86FA523F3054FF9D2BB5FE01566FFE7D" bold="true" box="[199,375,438,464]" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Biogeography:</emphasis>
Mexican transition zone (Sierra Madre del Sur province, Sierra Madre Occidental province); Neotropical region (Balsas Basin province).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FC94DDA63054FF9D2BB5FE4853EAFCB8" pageId="43" pageNumber="194" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B4318E2D3054FF9D2BB5FE4853EAFCB8" blockId="43.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">
<emphasis id="86FA523F3054FF9D2BB5FE485625FDB4" bold="true" box="[199,317,511,537]" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Remarks:</emphasis>
The transverse recession of the frons below the antennal scrobe carinae is noteworthy for this speciesgroup, which results in the antennal rims being recessed and essentially not visible when the head is viewed laterally; the clypeus is consequently also recessed. Members of the 
<taxonomicName id="738EF5AE3054FF9D2843FDF05487FDCD" authority="Linnaeus, 1758" authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1874" box="[817,927,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Mutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="194" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="satrapa">
<emphasis id="86FA523F3054FF9D2843FDF05487FDCD" box="[817,927,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">I. satrapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group also have this same transverse recession below the antennal scrobe carinae to varying degrees. Further, it is also observed in some unrelated 
<taxonomicName id="738EF5AE3054FF9D2E36FDDC561FFD04" baseAuthorityName="Lelej &amp; Nemkov" baseAuthorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="194" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pseudomethocini">Pseudomethocini</taxonomicName>
, such as several undescribed 
<taxonomicName id="738EF5AE3054FF9D2933FD3855F7FD04" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1896" box="[577,751,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Pseudomethoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="194" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="86FA523F3054FF9D2933FD3855F7FD04" box="[577,751,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Pseudomethoca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="86FA523F3054FF9D298FFD385471FD04" box="[765,873,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">sensu lato</emphasis>
) species, wherein the frons at or dorsad the antennal scrobe carinae is swollen, resulting in recessed antennal rims. The recessed antennal rim condition is manifested in its most extreme form in members of 
<taxonomicName id="738EF5AE3054FF9D2961FD605435FD5C" authority="Casal, 1962" authorityName="Casal" authorityYear="1962" box="[531,813,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Horcomutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="194" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="86FA523F3054FF9D2961FD6055BEFD5C" box="[531,678,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="194">Horcomutilla</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="D01FF3DC3054FF9D29DEFD605435FD5C" author="Casal, O. H." box="[684,813,727,753]" pageId="43" pageNumber="194" pagination="63 - 75" refId="ref36105" refString="Casal, O. H. (1962) Mutillidae Neotropicales, IX (Hymenoptera). Un nuevo genero de Sphaeropthalminae. Notas del Museo de La Plata, Zoologia, 20 (194), 63 - 75." type="journal article" year="1962">Casal, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
where the frons at the antennal scrobe carinae is swollen and anterad-projecting to varying degrees, with the antennal rims consequently being highly recessed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
